}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2868"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2871"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31346"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48139"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92616"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman attends her General Practice clinic for a health assessment and medication review. Her medical history is significant for well-controlled asthma, hypertension and notes poor dentition as a child for which she currently wears dentures, and also notes that she uses a hearing aid. She has a history of a clinically significant vertebral crush fracture earlier this year and a low-trauma fracture of her forearm two years prior. Her medication list includes a bisphosphonate, hydrochlorothiazide with salbutamol PRN. She is an ex-smoker with a 10-pack-year history and rarely drinks alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer last bone density scan showed a T-score -3.5 in her hip and -3.1 in her vertebra. Her examination is largely unremarkable, apart from a bluish discolouration to her sclerae.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of her bone density findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Genetic","Post-menopausal status","Exogenous glucocorticoid","Smoking","Vitamin D deficiency"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient likely has osteogenesis imperfecta type 1 as suggested by her history of osteoporosis and blue sclerae. Osteogenesis imperfecta type 1 may also be associated with dentinogenesis imperfecta and hearing loss, both of which are present in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOsteogenesis imperfecta type 1 is the mildest form of osteogenesis imperfecta, and in some cases may present only as accelerated post-menopausal osteoporosis. Other clinical presentations include poor dentition and hearing loss - due to disease of the ossicles in the inner ear. More severe forms may be associated with short stature, deformities such as scoliosis, valvular heart disease, joint laxity and easy bruising. Osteogenesis imperfecta type 1 is a \u003Cstrong\u003Egenetic\u003C/strong\u003E condition with autosomal dominant inheritance associated with COL1A1 or COL1A2 genes which are present in 90% of individuals with the disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of osteogenesis imperfecta type 1 requires multidisciplinary input to manage mobility, pain, reduce fracture risk and monitor dentition. Bisphosphonates are widely used for most types of osteogenesis imperfecta (not type IV), as they are potent inhibitors of bone turnover, which is increased in osteogenesis imperfecta. The clinical benefits of bisphosphonate use is likely to outweigh the risks, however they are not approved specifically for this use as the evidence for fracture reduction in adults is lacking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-menopausal\u003C/strong\u003E osteoporosis is a common aetiology in this demographic, however, given her other symptoms, it is less likely to be primary osteoporosis. Similarly, secondary causes such as \u003Cstrong\u003Emedications\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Evitamin D deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Esmoking\u003C/strong\u003E are less likely to be implicated in this case given the additional symptoms and signs consistent with osteogenesis imperfecta type 1.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Blue sclera, poor dentition, hearing loss and osteoporosis are suggestive of osteogenesis imperfecta"],"references":["Morton A. Blue eyes brittle bones. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2021;50:377-8. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2021/june/blue-eyes-brittle-bones"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75956"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2612"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75956"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T16:11:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T16:12:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2612"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92616"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"42","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/42"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"it